#TEMPERATURE EFFECT ON PREDATION IN THE GALAPAGOS

In this study we measured the role of temperature on moderating predation in a system exposed to seasonal upwelling, The Galapagos, both in the lab and the field.

In this documents we show the code for:

  1. Building a map with the locations where we collected specimens, conducted lab experiments, and field experiments
  2. Building a plot with the temperature variation in the site where we collected organisms and conducted field experiment, La Barcaza, a rocky reefs north of San Cristobal.
  3. Statistically comparing results from our lab experiment, where we conducted predation trials at 4 temperatures.We include plot use to graphically compared these results, and we compared feeding rates and movement.
  4. Statistically comparing results from our lab experiment, where we conducted predation trials at 4 temperatures. We include plot use to graphically compared these results.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  lab_exp$BarnacleEatenPerDay
## W = 0.78112, p-value = 6.559e-05

My data is no normal, what model to use? Data is quite skewed to the left, so probably a glm with gamma data would be the most useful. For gamma distribution we cannot have zeros, so make sure that we add a constat (+1) when conducting our model. We cannot use poison because poisson requires number with no decimals, only for counting data. Our data was count, however, we conducted experiments with different amount of time, so we are normalizing by predation per day, and that is the reason we have decimal numbers. We did poisson models using the offset parameters also, just to compared with our results from the gamma model.

Modelling effect of temperature on lab predation rates

#modelo poisson 
model_poisson<-glm(BarnacleEaten~Treatment+offset(log(DaysExperiment)), family=quasipoisson(link="log"), data=lab_exp) # we use offset because Poisson model only can consider number without decimals.
summary(model_poisson) #model conclude every temperature is different from 16C

Plot showing the effect of temperature on predation rates in the lab

We will build a plot showing mean from each treatmment with standard error (sd/sqrt(n)), indicating significance differences.

#let's summarise mean, sd, and calculate se

lab_exp$Treatment<-relevel(lab_exp$Treatment, ref="16") # we are releveling so our plot is in order 

levels(lab_exp$Treatment)
## [1] "16" "28" "26" "21"
lab_exp$Treatment<-factor(lab_exp$Treatment, levels=c("16", "21", "26", "28"))
levels(lab_exp$Treatment)
## [1] "16" "21" "26" "28"
summary_lab_exp<-lab_exp %>%
  dplyr::select(BarnacleEatenPerDay, Treatment, n) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(Treatment)%>%
  dplyr::summarise(mean=mean(BarnacleEatenPerDay), sd=sd(BarnacleEatenPerDay), n=mean(n)) %>%
    dplyr::mutate(se=sd/sqrt(n))

head(lab_exp)

plot_FR_lab<-ggplot()+

Lets glimpse at how data is distributed

hist(field_exp_filter$DailyPredation)

Similarly to the lab experiment, our data seems very skewed toward the left (many whelks dont eat and most of the one who eats, eats very little). Considering, a glm with family=Gamma is the best option. Again, I have to add 0.01 to make sure I dont have zeros.

We also have a very unbalanced design where we have three levels of a predation treatment (20 and 27) for two temperature but only one for another (24C). One good option could be to run each predation treatment alone through the temperature levels.
